{"id":"1505.05133","submitter":"Mike Williams","authors":"Baptiste Guegan, John Hardin, Justin Stevens and Mike Williams","title":"Model selection for amplitude analysis","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1748-0221/10/09/P09002","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.data-an hep-ex","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Model complexity in amplitude analyses is often a priori under-constrained\nsince the underlying theory permits a large number of possible amplitudes to\ncontribute to most physical processes. The use of an overly complex model\nresults in reduced predictive power and worse resolution on unknown parameters\nof interest. Therefore, it is common to reduce the complexity by removing from\nconsideration some subset of the allowed amplitudes. This paper studies a\nmethod for limiting model complexity from the data sample itself through\nregularization during regression in the context of a multivariate (Dalitz-plot)\nanalysis. The regularization technique applied greatly improves the\nperformance. An outline of how to obtain the significance of a resonance in a\nmultivariate amplitude analysis is also provided.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 15 May 2015 17:54:13 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 17 Aug 2015 14:57:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-09-30"}
{"id":"1505.05495","submitter":"Somenath Chakrabarty","authors":"Sanchari De and Somenath Chakrabarty","title":"Schr\\\"odinger Equation of a particle in an Uniformly Accelerated Frame\n  and the Possibility of a New kind of Quanta","comments":"7 pages, No figure, To appear in Modern Physics Letter A","journal-ref":"Mod. Phys. Lett Vol 30 (38) (2015) Page:1550182","doi":"10.1142/S0217732315501825","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc astro-ph.HE quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this article we have developed a formalism to obtain the\nSchr$\\ddot{\\rm{o}}$dinger equation for a particle in a frame undergoing an\nuniform acceleration in an otherwise flat Minkowski space-time geometry. We\nhave presented an exact solution of the equation and obtained the\neigenfunctions and the corresponding eigenvalues. It has been observed that the\nSchr$\\ddot{\\rm{o}}$dinger equation can be reduced to an one dimensional\nhydrogen atom problem. Whereas, the quantized energy levels are exactly\nidentical with that of an one dimensional quantum harmonic oscillator. Hence\nconsidering transitions, we have predicted the existence of a new kind of\nquanta, which will either be emitted or absorbed if the particles get excited\nor de-excited respectively.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 16 May 2015 11:00:32 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 1 Aug 2015 07:12:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-12-02"}
{"id":"1506.00538","submitter":"Alexander Karimov","authors":"A.R. Karimov and H. Schamel","title":"The successive formation and disappearance of density structures in\n  simple expanding systems","comments":"15 pages, 2 figures, submitted to the Physica Scripta","journal-ref":"Physica Scripta Volume 90 Number 9 095201 (2015)","doi":"10.1088/0031-8949/90/9/095201","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.plasm-ph nlin.AO physics.class-ph physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Lagrangian fluid description is employed to solve the initial value\nproblem for one-dimensional, compressible fluid flows represented by the\nEuler-Poisson system. Exact nonlinear and time-dependent solutions are\nobtained, which exhibit a variety of transient phenomena such as a density\ncollapse in finite space-time or the appearance and, for the first time, a\nsuccessive dissolution of wavelet structures during the same event. The latter\nare superimposed on the gross density pattern in the course of the\nuni-directional expansion of an initially localized density hump. Whereas\nself-gravitating fluids will always experience collapse, neutral fluids and\nfluids with repulsive forces, such as a non-neutral, pure electron fluid, can\nexhibit an evolution of the second type, being determined by the initial\nconditions. For an electron fluid, being embedded in a neutralizing ion\nbackground, these nonlinearities are, however, strongly diminished due to the\nomnipresent plasma oscillations, which weaken and alternatively change the sign\nof the collective force.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 16 May 2015 09:41:57 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-09-06"}
